04509nmm a2200649Ia 9780814762462DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147624627 a10.18574/nyu/9780814762462.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681170  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF4217.I46bO43 2012 7aLAW0320002bisacsh04a344.73/07912231 aOlivas, Michael A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Undocumented Child Left Behind :bPlyler v. Doe and the Education of Undocumented Schoolchildren /cMichael A. Olivas. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCitizenship and Migration in the Americas ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Why Plyler Matters -- t2 The Story of Plyler v. Doe: The Education of Undocumented Children and the Polity -- t3 The Implementation of Plyler v. Doe -- t4 The Political Economy of the DREAM Act and the Legislative Process: Doe Goes to College -- t5 Conclusion: The Discourse and the Danger (or, Why Plyler Should Have Been Decided on Preemption Grounds) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1982 U. S. Supreme Court case of Plyler v. Doe, which made it possible for undocumented children to enroll in Texas public schools, was a watershed moment for immigrant rights in the United States. The Court struck down both a state statute denying funding for education to undocumented children and a municipal school district's attempt to charge an annual $1,000 tuition fee for each undocumented student to compensate for the lost state funding. Yet while this case has not returned to the Supreme Court, it is frequently contested at the state and local level.In No Undocumented Child Left Behind, Michael A. Olivas tells a fascinating history of the landmark case, examining how, 30 years later, Plyler v. Doe continues to suffer from implementation issues and requires additional litigation and vigilance to enforce the ruling. He takes a comprehensive look at the legal regime it established regarding the education of undocumented school children, moves up through its implementation, including direct and indirect attacks on it, and closes with the ongoing, highly charged debates over the Development, Relief, and Education for Minors (DREAM) Act, which aims to give conditional citizenship to undocumented college students who graduated from US high schools and have been in the country for at least five years. Listen to Michael Olivas on WYPF 88.1 FM, as he takes a look back 30 years to the Supreme Court case that made it possible for undocumented children to enroll in public schools and the highly-charged political and legal battles that have ensued.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of illegal aliensxEducationxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aChildren of illegal aliensxEducationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aChildren of noncitizensxEducationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aIllegal immigrationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aNoncitizens. 7aLAW / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814762462.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814762462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814762462/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles